01:04.263 --> 01:06.298
No.

01:15.491 --> 01:20.279
There is no Cervantes.
There is no Susan Connors.

01:22.982 --> 01:24.166
No, wait, wait.

01:24.250 --> 01:27.019
Your boss kidnapped

01:27.086 --> 01:28.587
a journalist
from her hotel room

01:28.655 --> 01:30.422
in Asuncion
four days ago.

01:30.490 --> 01:34.126
<i>Now, that journalist happens
to be a friend of mine.</i>

01:34.193 --> 01:38.130
And I'm prepared to pay
an <i>obscene</i> amount of money.

01:38.181 --> 01:39.564
So don't be stupid.

01:43.903 --> 01:47.406
You are being sent home
as a courtesy.

01:47.473 --> 01:51.843
Most who make it this far
aren't so lucky.

01:51.911 --> 01:55.347
Don't come back.

02:02.355 --> 02:04.056
I'm sorry. You went where?

02:04.123 --> 02:06.391
<i>Because I thought you said
that you tried</i>

02:06.459 --> 02:08.092
<i>to see Miguel Cervantes,</i>

02:08.161 --> 02:09.961
the most dangerous warlord
on The Triple Frontier,

02:10.029 --> 02:11.296
which is saying something,

02:11.364 --> 02:13.365
and that you did it alone.

02:13.433 --> 02:16.068
- Yes.
- Help me out here

02:16.135 --> 02:17.669
'cause when we discussed this
the other day,

02:17.737 --> 02:18.970
I explained to you
that no one knows

02:19.038 --> 02:19.971
where to find Cervantes.

02:20.039 --> 02:21.340
Yes.

02:21.407 --> 02:24.376
And that they kill people
down there for even asking.

02:25.645 --> 02:28.580
You're worried about me.

02:28.648 --> 02:30.649
I'm worried about who's gonna
pay the bills around here

02:30.717 --> 02:31.650
if you end up dead

02:31.718 --> 02:33.985
<i>in some South American gutter</i>

02:34.053 --> 02:35.187
somewhere.

02:37.190 --> 02:39.224
It's been almost five days
since Susan went missing

02:39.275 --> 02:40.926
investigating a story
about Cervantes.

02:40.993 --> 02:42.227
And we all agree
that if Cervantes

02:42.295 --> 02:44.162
simply wanted her dead,
he would've done it publicly.

02:44.230 --> 02:45.997
- So she's probably still alive.
- Probably.

02:46.065 --> 02:47.766
The State Department can't act
because they have no way

02:47.834 --> 02:49.301
of getting a message
to him.

02:49.369 --> 02:51.737
The local governments won't act
because they're afraid of him.

02:51.804 --> 02:53.238
And when I asked you
about rescue options,

02:53.306 --> 02:54.623
you said there weren't any.

02:54.707 --> 02:56.174
Well, I meant
that I couldn't think of any.

02:56.242 --> 02:57.175
Well,
what's the difference?

02:57.243 --> 02:58.176
In the interim,

02:58.244 --> 03:00.645
I may have thought of one.

03:03.216 --> 03:05.083
Well, what is it?

03:05.151 --> 03:06.651
I've known this woman
since we were children.

03:06.719 --> 03:08.753
Well, it's a little
unorthodox.

03:08.805 --> 03:11.423
You might not like it.
But could be worth a try.

03:11.474 --> 03:12.441
<i>No.</i>

03:12.525 --> 03:14.025
No.

03:14.093 --> 03:15.127
Hell, no.

03:15.194 --> 03:17.763
- Oh, you got my note.
- <i>Yeah, I got your note.</i>

03:17.830 --> 03:21.500
Bad idea.
Terrible idea.

03:21.567 --> 03:23.535
- I won't be a part of it.
- Won't be a part of what?

03:26.172 --> 03:27.873
All right, let's just start
at the beginning.

03:27.940 --> 03:29.107
A few years ago,

03:29.175 --> 03:31.143
Miguel Cervantes
hired an assassin to take out

03:31.210 --> 03:33.345
<i>the President of Paraguay.</i>

03:33.413 --> 03:34.446
The assassin was successful.

03:34.514 --> 03:36.314
Was quite proud of himself,
I might add.

03:36.382 --> 03:37.883
We're talking about you.

03:37.950 --> 03:40.852
No. Wasn't me.

03:40.920 --> 03:42.020
<i>It was a guy I know.</i>

03:42.088 --> 03:44.923
Anyway, Cervantes
and this assassin

03:44.991 --> 03:46.658
had a falling out.

03:46.726 --> 03:47.659
Define falling out.

03:47.727 --> 03:48.793
Cervantes tried to kill him.

03:48.845 --> 03:50.028
<i>Which means</i>

03:50.096 --> 03:52.130
that the assassin

03:52.198 --> 03:54.032
might be inclined
to help us stage a rescue.

03:54.100 --> 03:55.333
<i>Dude.</i>

03:55.401 --> 03:57.736
No. I mean, seriously.

03:58.684 --> 03:59.504
<i>This guy's a bad egg.</i>

03:59.604 --> 04:01.872
- You can't trust him.
- Really?

04:01.940 --> 04:03.874
You see
what's happening here?

04:03.942 --> 04:05.409
<i>We</i> agree.

04:05.477 --> 04:07.511
Now imagine
how that makes me feel.

04:07.579 --> 04:09.346
You think I'm happy
about this?

04:09.414 --> 04:10.648
I didn't want
to see him again

04:10.715 --> 04:11.715
let alone ask him for help.

04:11.783 --> 04:12.716
But the lady

04:12.784 --> 04:14.485
wants to get
her friend back

04:14.552 --> 04:16.019
so I don't have
any better ideas.

04:16.087 --> 04:17.588
Do you?
<i>Will someone please tell me</i>

04:17.656 --> 04:18.755
what's going on here?

04:18.822 --> 04:20.057
<i>Who is this guy</i>

04:20.125 --> 04:21.725
and why is it such a big deal
to ask for his help?

04:21.793 --> 04:22.760
He was picked up
by the FBI

04:22.827 --> 04:24.528
then he was traded
to the Russians.

04:24.596 --> 04:30.017
Apparently they wanted him
more than our guys did.

04:30.101 --> 04:31.869
He's not gonna be easy
to get to,

04:31.936 --> 04:34.505
but I just don't see
any other way.

04:41.680 --> 04:43.113
<i>Spasiba.</i>

04:43.181 --> 04:45.616
So the only person
who can help rescue Susan

04:45.684 --> 04:47.017
is a professional killer

04:47.085 --> 04:48.352
you neither like nor trust

04:48.420 --> 04:50.020
who's currently rotting
in a Siberian prison,

04:50.088 --> 04:51.622
and these two think
you're completely crazy

04:51.690 --> 04:52.656
for even suggesting it.

04:52.724 --> 04:53.991
Is that a vaguely
accurate picture

04:54.059 --> 04:56.093
of what we're talking
about here?

04:56.161 --> 04:58.028
Pretty much.

04:59.097 --> 05:00.864
Oh, last time I saw him,

05:00.932 --> 05:01.932
we tried to kill each other.

05:02.000 --> 05:03.701
Look,
I know it sounds bad.

05:03.768 --> 05:05.636
But if we're gonna stage
a rescue for Susan, I think--

05:05.704 --> 05:07.438
Do it.

05:08.773 --> 05:12.009
Whatever it takes.

05:12.060 --> 05:15.346
We have to get Susan
out of there alive.

05:16.715 --> 05:18.482
Just out of curiosity,

05:18.550 --> 05:21.819
can you tell me the name
of this assassin?

05:21.886 --> 05:25.222
Well, he goes by several names.

05:25.290 --> 05:27.057
But the one
I know him by is...

05:27.125 --> 05:29.360
Baptiste.

05:33.198 --> 05:34.965
Hello, matey.

